§ 0  WHY THIS TOURNAMENT EXISTS
───────────────────────────────
Alice's clock today is an adult-human-Western-business-day clock with
millisecond UTC ticks. That is one species, one culture, one timebase.
Biological organisms perceive time at radically different rates because
their nervous systems sample the world at radically different rates. A
hummingbird reading 80 frames per second of Architect motion is not
having "the same experience faster"; it is in a different temporal
universe. Our swarm should be able to inhabit any of these universes
on demand — the way Alice already inhabits any mood on demand via the
endocrine ledger.

This tournament adds six concrete organs grounded in six canonical
papers. Three are white-space (nobody in the swarm has built them yet).
Two upgrade existing organs against the actual literature. One opens
a bridge between the endocrine layer and the clock layer.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
§ 1  THE SIX CANONICAL PAPERS (with what they actually say)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

[P1] Healy, K., McNally, L., Ruxton, G. D., Cooper, N., & Jackson, A. L.
     (2013). "Metabolic rate and body size are linked with perception of
     temporal information." Animal Behaviour, 86(4), 685–696.
     https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0003347213003060

     KEY CLAIM
     Critical Flicker Fusion frequency (CFF) — the highest flicker rate
     at which a flashing light is perceived as steady — scales with
     metabolic rate (positive) and body mass (negative) across 30+
     vertebrate species. Higher metabolism + smaller body = higher CFF
     = more "frames per second" of subjective experience.

     CROSS-SPECIES NUMBERS (from the paper + standard references)
       Pied flycatcher          : ~146 Hz   (highest measured vertebrate)
       European starling        : ~100 Hz
       Dog                      :  ~75 Hz
       Cat                      :  ~55 Hz
       Human (cone-mediated)    :  ~60 Hz
       Salt-water fishes        :  ~14–35 Hz
       Leatherback sea turtle   :  ~15 Hz
       Eel                      :  ~14 Hz
       (Insects, separate lit)  : flies ~250 Hz
     A hummingbird sees Architect's hand-gesture at ~3-4× human resolution.
     A leatherback sea turtle sees it at ~1/4 human resolution.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     Alice's inference cadence (currently a fixed asyncio loop) should be
     configurable to a "species CFF" parameter. At human CFF (~60Hz), the
     widget streams replies the way it does now. At hummingbird CFF (~80Hz),
     she would refresh sensory ledgers ~33% more often and her "now" window
     would shrink. At leatherback CFF (~15Hz), her present moment would be
     ~4× longer and she would batch incoming utterances differently.

[P2] Buhusi, C. V. & Meck, W. H. (2005). "What makes us tick?
     Functional and neural mechanisms of interval timing."
     Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 6(10), 755–765.
     https://www.nature.com/articles/nrn1764

     KEY CLAIMS
       (a) Mammals have THREE separate clocks: circadian (SCN, ~24h),
           interval (cortico-striatal, milliseconds–hours), and
           millisecond (cerebellum).
       (b) Interval timing obeys the SCALAR PROPERTY (Weber's law for
           time): the standard deviation of duration estimates grows
           linearly with the duration estimated. Coefficient of variation
           ~0.15–0.30 across species.
       (c) The PACEMAKER-ACCUMULATOR model: a pacemaker emits pulses,
           an accumulator counts them, working memory stores the count,
           a comparator decides "long enough yet?".
       (d) DOPAMINE manipulates the pacemaker rate (clock-stage effect).
           Cholinergic manipulation shifts memory-stage. This is why
           Parkinsonian patients underestimate intervals: low DA → slow
           pacemaker.
       (e) The STRIATAL BEAT-FREQUENCY MODEL: rather than one pacemaker,
           thousands of cortical oscillators of different frequencies fire
           together at one moment, then drift out of phase, then beat back
           into coincidence at the criterion interval. Striatal medium
           spiny neurons act as coincidence detectors.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     We have endocrine glands (DA, cortisol, etc.) and we have heartbeats,
     but we have no PACEMAKER-ACCUMULATOR organ that produces interval
     estimates with the scalar property, and no DOPAMINE → CLOCK-RATE
     bridge that would make Alice tick faster when excited and slower
     when depleted.

[P3] Stetson, C., Fiesta, M. P. & Eagleman, D. M. (2007). "Does time
     really slow down during a frightening event?" PLoS ONE, 2(12), e1295.
     https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2110887/

     KEY CLAIM (commonly misquoted!)
     This paper FALSIFIES the folk-psych "time slows in fear" hypothesis.
     Subjects in 31m free-fall (yes, the SCAD-tower experiment) reported
     their own falls as ~36% longer than they reported others' falls — but
     when given a wrist device that flashed numbers at frequencies beyond
     their normal perceptual threshold, they could NOT read the faster
     numbers during the fall. Perceptual temporal resolution did not
     increase. The dilation is RECONSTRUCTIVE: high-arousal events lay
     down denser memories, and "duration" is reconstructed at recall from
     memory density.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     AG31's `swarm_temporal_chronometry.py` already cites Eagleman, and
     it uses MEMORY DENSITY as the dilation signal — which matches the
     paper. The CFF / perceptual side is correctly NOT modulated. AG31
     read the literature right. Worth verifying the comment says so —
     because the folk-psych version (real-time perception speeds up
     under fear) is WRONG and we must not regress to it.

[P4] Pöppel, E. (1997, 2009). "A hierarchical model of temporal
     perception" / "Pre-semantically defined temporal windows for
     cognitive processing." Trends Cogn Sci 1(2), 56–61 / Phil Trans
     R Soc B 364, 1887–1896.
     (Critical review: White, P. A., 2017. "The three-second
     'subjective present': a critical review and a new proposal."
     Psychological Bulletin 143(7), 735–756.)
     https://www.ernst-poeppel.com/opinions/retrospection-of-research-and-perspectives-1/
     https://orca.cardiff.ac.uk/id/eprint/98445/1/Peter%20White%20three-second%20moment%20paper%203.pdf

     KEY CLAIM
     Subjective "now" is not an instant — it is a window of approximately
     3 seconds during which events are bound into a single perceptual unit.
     Below 3 ms: simultaneity. 30 ms: order. ~3 s: present. Beyond 3 s:
     past. Music phrasing, conversational turn-taking, and breathing all
     cluster at this scale.

     White's 2017 review tempers Pöppel: the integration window is not
     fixed at 3 s but DEPENDS ON INFORMATION DENSITY — sparser stimuli
     get integrated over longer windows, denser ones over shorter.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     Alice has no explicit `present_window_ms` parameter. Her "now" is
     implicitly whatever the most recent ledger sample returned. If we
     define `subjective_present_window_s` derived from CFF (smaller
     animals have shorter windows, ~1/CFF × constant), we get a
     species-tunable specious-present that can replace the magic
     `SIFTA_DIALOGUE_CONTEXT_WINDOW_S=600` constant with a biologically
     grounded one.

[P5] Gibbon, J. (1977). "Scalar expectancy theory and Weber's law in
     animal timing." Psychological Review, 84(3), 279–325.
     https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1977-25224-001

     KEY CLAIM
     Foundational. The single theoretical paper that started interval
     timing as a quantitative field. Animals timing fixed intervals
     (rats pressing levers, pigeons pecking keys) produce response
     distributions whose standard deviation scales LINEARLY with the
     interval mean — the SCALAR PROPERTY. Same coefficient of variation
     across rats, pigeons, mice, monkeys, humans. It is one of the
     most general laws in behavioral neuroscience.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     If Alice estimates "5 minutes since you spoke", her error should
     be ~5 × CV (where CV ≈ 0.2) = ±1 minute. Right now she has zero
     such estimator and would either say "5.0000000 minutes" (machine
     precision lie) or "I don't know". Neither is biological.

[P6] Matell, M. S. & Meck, W. H. (2004). "Cortico-striatal circuits
     and interval timing: coincidence detection of oscillatory
     processes." Cognitive Brain Research 21(2), 139–170.
     https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15464348/

     KEY CLAIM
     The Striatal Beat-Frequency model in mathematical form. N cortical
     oscillators with frequencies f_i fire in phase at t=0, then drift
     out of phase, then come back into phase at the least common
     multiple of their periods. Striatal MSNs detect this coincidence
     pattern via Hebbian synapses. Net effect: a mechanism that can
     learn ARBITRARY criterion intervals just by changing which
     coincidence pattern is rewarded — no separate clock per interval.

     IMPLICATION FOR SWARM
     This is the most code-able of all six. A list of N float
     oscillators, a phase update each tick, a coincidence kernel, a
     learnable criterion-pattern memory. ~150 lines of Python.

