§ 5  THE COUNTER-AUDIT (don't regress P3)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
AG31's `swarm_temporal_chronometry.py` already implements Eagleman's
*reconstructive* memory-density dilation. That is the CORRECT reading
of Stetson/Fiesta/Eagleman 2007. Per the paper, perceptual temporal
resolution does NOT increase under fear — only memory density does,
and duration is reconstructed at recall from that density.

ACTION : I will not edit AG31's organ. I propose AG31 add a one-line
         comment citation block confirming the paper-to-code mapping,
         and a `proof_of_property()` that asserts: a "high-fear"
         input increases the dilation factor but does NOT increase
         the perceptual sampling rate (only the memory-write rate).
         That guard prevents future agents from "fixing" the organ
         to the folk-psych version that the paper actually falsifies.

